Communism Makes a Comeback in Russia
Moscow—More than a year ago, during a sabbatical from the American university where I was teaching, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of free speech.
But once upon a time, this place still retained some freedoms.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled the country in an attempt to gain the support of politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Protests erupted among the people.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely regarded as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was banned for "extremism," while its members are being exiled or investigated.
Almost every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agent" list —— and even worse —— listed as "unwelcome individuals."
In the past year, Russia has slipped into a non-free state, although not far away, but very fiercely.
For example, a law designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aiming to undermine or discredit organizations or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the extent that forwarding a tweet is now also a reason for being labeled a foreign agent.
(Being labeled as an "unwanted person" can lead to complete prohibition.
) Just this year alone, the list of foreign agents saw a record addition of 101 entities.
The cumulative total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be included on the list because they "influence the country's politics."
But of course, the core objective of news and propaganda work is to influence politics.
This is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, the only true opposition group to emerge from the Kremlin is an unlikely one — the Communist Party.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — encouraging people to support forces most likely to defeat candidates backed by the Kremlin — and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data show that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the vote in the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the voting results were manipulated.
Factually, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original communists.
Not only do they not deny worldly pleasures, but members are dressed in fur coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some are millionaires — for example, the charismatic agricultural chief Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's election).
Although the party is still led by 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
Nicknamed "Red Navalny," 36-year-old Bondarenko strongly criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister said Russians should be able to "eat better" on a salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50) per month, Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove the man wrong on his own YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban on running, Bondarenko was allowed to participate in the State Duma elections last month.
Although he had the support of Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the candidate from United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently came up with a title for a protest, accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
Then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarenko, she surprisingly lost the last election.
But she remains — and is becoming even more — popular.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Englichieva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects people's yearning for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks had promised justice and equality, and although the country that realized these ideals was strict, it was not lacking in fairness and compassion.
Furthermore, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which the whims of an individual would not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly joining forces: forming a "United Russia" that can oppose Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as the Czech Donald Trump — failed to secure re-election as prime minister, as the opposition coalition set aside their ideological differences and formed a united alliance, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition coalition.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also prepare a unified electoral list for the parliamentary elections next year and field a single candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, toppling Putin will be far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that more comprehensive measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party will be taken.
But the above approach also brings risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not died," and points to the existence of an "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he is at least still interested in pretending that Russia has not been driven toward something nearly authoritarian.
Putin says he only wants stability.
However, his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin is as capricious in making and implementing rules toward the communists as it has been toward Russian liberals, driving them underground, then a social explosion is more likely to occur.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Russians communists — yes, communists — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
